Most document folders start simple.

A few PDFs. Some notes. A handful of CSVs. Then the folder grows into a working archive with no real structure beyond filenames and memory.

Search breaks first.

You remember a concept, not the exact file.
You remember a company name, not which report mentioned it.
You remember that two documents were related, but not why.

A useful fix is to turn the folder into a lightweight knowledge graph.

Not a giant enterprise graph.
Not a research project.
A practical local graph that connects files, entities, and keywords so you can query relationships instead of scanning filenames.

This article builds that system in Python.

⸻

What this solves

A normal folder gives you storage.

A document graph gives you structure:

• Which files mention the same people, companies, or topics
• Which notes are closely related even if their filenames differ
• Which documents act as bridges between themes
• Which terms dominate a project folder
• Which files should appear together in search results

The approach is simple:

• Read text files from a folder
• Extract entities and keywords
• Build a graph with NetworkX
• Add similarity links between related documents
• Query the graph for useful answers

This works well for:

• research notes
• project documentation
• meeting archives
• legal or policy text collections
• personal knowledge bases
• small team document repositories

⸻

The graph design

We will create three node types:

• document
• entity
• keyword

And three edge types:

• mentions → document to entity
• has_keyword → document to keyword
• similar_to → document to document

This gives enough structure to answer questions like:

• Which documents mention the same organization?
• What are the most central entities in this folder?
• Which files are semantically close to a given note?
• Which keywords connect otherwise separate clusters?

⸻

